subSubSection.paragraph:
upperparts. Hindfeet are brown. Tail is ¢.45% of head—body length, thickened at base, blackish, and not bicolored. Tail has numerous long bristle hairs for three-quarters of its length (pilosity 70-80%). Skull is large and heavy, with somewhat arched rather than straight dorsal profile. Interorbital region is broad, and sagittal crest is well developed and extends forward nearly to nasals. Dentition is heavy but less so than in the African Giant White-toothed Shrew (
C. olivieri
). Second upper unicuspid is slightly larger than third.
